{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "One common approach is the arithmetic averaging of the models' outputs, as discussed in [11] for recurrent neural networks (RNNs).",
    "An alternative approach is weighted averaging, where higher weights are assigned to models whose predictions were more accurate in past data [12].",
    "However, as these methods select a static weighting, they may be suboptimal in predictive control Laura Boca de Giuli, Alessio La Bella, and Riccardo Scattolini are with the Dipartimento di Elettronica, Informazione e Bioingegneria, Politecnico di Milano, 20133 Milan, Italy (e-mails: laura.bocadegiuli@polimi.it, alessio.labella@polimi.it, and riccardo.scattolini@polimi.it).Samuel Mallick, Azita Dabiri and Bart De Schutter are with the Delft Center for Systems and Control, Delft University of Technology, The Netherlands (emails: s.h.mallick@tudelft.nl, a.dabiri@tudelft.nl, and b.deschutter@tudelft.nl.",
    "frameworks such as MPC [13], where the weighting should ideally vary across the prediction window.",
    "To this end, more advanced methods dynamically optimize the combination weights with gating networks [14], e.g., using generic artificial neural networks [15] or Bayesian neural networks [16]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "One common approach is the arithmetic averaging of the models' outputs, as discussed in [11] for recurrent neural networks (RNNs).",
    "An alternative approach is weighted averaging, where higher weights are assigned to models whose predictions were more accurate in past data [12].",
    "frameworks such as MPC [13], where the weighting should ideally vary across the prediction window.",
    "To this end, more advanced methods dynamically optimize the combination weights with gating networks [14], e.g., using generic artificial neural networks [15] or Bayesian neural networks [16]."
  ]
